''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''Multiple Linear Estimation (MLE)''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''''
                         '''''''MLE uses OLS estimation approach''''''''''''''''''''''''''''
                       '''' the three equations represent supply and demand, (production, monetary and services sector)''''''''

'''''''''''''''the forecast equation for MLE'----------------------------------------------
pageselect Quarterly
smpl 2012q1 2026q1

equation eq_mle1.ls dlog(real_gdp) dlog(ar_cpi_food_f) dlog(ar_turnovers_trade_f) dlog(ar_turnovers_services_f) c

equation eq_mle2.ls dlog(real_gdp) dlog(ar_m3_f) dlog(ar_credit_priv_sector_f) dlog(ar_cpi_f) c

equation eq_mle3.ls dlog(real_gdp) dlog(AR_TURNOVERS_CONSTRUCT_F )  dlog(ar_agriculture_exp_val_f ) dlog(AR_M3_F )  c

'''''''''''''''''''forecasting MLE equations in level-------------------------

smpl 2010q1 2026q1

EQ_MLE1.forecast(e, g) in_real_gdpmle1_f
EQ_MLE2.forecast(e, g) in_real_gdpmle2_f
EQ_MLE3.forecast(e, g) in_real_gdpmle3_f

'''''''''''''forecast evaluation of MLE-------select the method with least forecast error for forecast averaging
smpl 2012q1 2026q1
